reviews.text: The drive to and the actual place is gorgeous. The scenery is as if from a post card
I thought I would find a better point of view on the lighthouse, but still an interesting spot

This is definitely a must stop while doing wedding photography. It contains multiple angles within few steps. Only drawback is the amount of people around never stops, definitely not a great location if you can't wait, otherwise don't miss it. Photos by Farawayland weddings.
Very nice spot.. despite the sewer outflow. I farted loudly and horrified a passing family.. for which I'm forever sorry
Overhyped. You've much better views from all around the park. Sea wall and the lighthouse weren't really as charming and they're put out to be

What to do and where to go in VANCOUVER!! 
A Wonderful place to visit and enjoy the views of the NEW  Vancouver Convention Center, North Shore mountains, watch the Sea planes land and take off. A great place to people watch while you sip a cup of your favorite mocha and enjoy the bites. Go for a walk down the CANADIAN TRAIL. And make you way to the end of the trail for some great views. This a must see for visitors to the Vancouver area. One of my favorite places to take friends and families when they are visiting our special beautiful city. Watch for more of my reviews under the headline-
What to do in VANCOUVER!!
You can then Enjoy the Fly Over Canada experience as well. The movies are often changing so catch something different. And tell your friends about it also. 
Pls give me a like 👍if you read this! Thanks

One of the MUST GO scenic spots to visit in Vancouver.
There are always stuffs guiding people in the building.
You wouldn’t worry to get lost.
And man! The view is amazing. 
Must give a try on Fly Canada, very unique experience.

This is a great part of Vancouver! You can see amazing views from outside the convention centre itself, out toward the ski mountains, water, and Stanley Park. There is lots of room inside the convention centre, and because it's connected to the Pan Pacific Hotel there is lots of room to walk around and explore the lobby of that as well. Very roomy and well-kept inside Canada Place, and the layout totally makes sense.
It's touristy but so much fun. Great vibe. An iconic landmark. And so beautifully blue

This is a great tourist place. I visited this place with my family and had a lot of fun!!

 We place a game of matching pictures with provinces and got free stickers, badges and temporary tattoos!

It's a perfect length walk and usually very busy! It is super pretty at night! I wish it was open a little bit later!

If you're new in Vancouver you shortly definitely visit this place!

Took my nephew this year and had an amazing time. He's 6 years old and thought it was the greatest thing! There's lots fun free stuff for children to do. We had a blast in the arts n crafts igloo. I highly recommend doing the scavenger treasure hunt (we won a free carousal ride!) Also the berry kinder punch is perfect for those who don't drink alcohol! Great affordable event compared to some of the other events we tried in Vancouver

Vancouver Christmas Market...
We went today to Experience what we had been told was a great market for the Season. My impression?
Not that many actual Maker/Sellers.
As many food merchants as Craft Marketeers.
Plus one major retailer - a true German Retail giant. Though entry required at least a half hour line up.
And the displays and Features are fun!
But really, is that service and experience worth such an entrance charge? Yes, the fee does allow entry for multiple days. But is there anything worth returning to?
Well, once is an Experience. And I've had it now.

If you're coming here because you miss the Christmas markets in Europe - don't come here, the prices (of entry & everything inside) will shock you. However, if you've only been to Christmas markets in Vancouver, this is definitely a fun & memorable experience. Many of the stores are European themed, but local products are sold here too so you might find some unique Christmas gifts. The live music with the mulled wine creates quite a cheerful atmosphere which is almost unique to Christmas.
It's not a terribly big market, so adults will probably find one visit enough  but families might benefit from the season pass. Regardless, be prepared to make a dent to the wallet at the market.

I used to LOVE this market. Its entry fee used to be $2, season's pass included. It has gone downhill from there. The vendors got worse (used to be way more German ornament stands). The price keeps going up but what's inside stays the same. And yes, you are not publicly funded neither are most other businesses and they don't hijack their prices to that extent. Honestly, $15 to get in? I used to tell everyone they must go there, I would make several visits a season myself and bring new people with me but over the last few years, this year especially, I found it harder and harder to defend their price increases and the need/want to actually go there. Honestly, I don't recommend it anymore. I feel bad for the vendors as they pay to be there and only have a month to sell off their goods, it's hard for them to keep their prices steady. Some travel in from Europe. Vancouver German Christmas Market, you need to do better. Go back to a smaller venue if needed but prices need to come down if you wish to keep your client base. Sure tourists may go there but the locals are definitely opting out.

Lovely place! Amazing what they have put together. You will defiantly find your heart‘s desire there! The wide choice of food and beverage will blow your mind. In my opinion it’s even worth going there on a rainy day, since there is plenty of space where you can sit inside, stand by the fire and enjoy your hot drink. Extremely family friendly as well! The people are so kind that you don’t have a choice but to go home with a smile on your face. That’s what it’s all about :)

Beautiful spot, you are able to get to this spot without needing a car since the bussing system can take you there. Great easy walk to get the full views of Vancouver. You can see the sea wall and the city skyline with just one easy walk. Lots of parking if you do take a car. There were people landing planes in the water when we were there, pretty interesting to watch. They have bike lanes and walking lanes for safety

Ideally located on a peninsula at the northwestern edge of downtown Vancouver, Stanley Park is one of the city’s main tourist destination. Featuring lovely beaches, miles of well maintained paved and dirt trails, Canada’s largest aquarium and an array of can’t miss kids friendly spots. It is recognized as one of the greatest urban parks in the world.

Fantastic Green Space with a wonderfully maintained aquarium that is the gold standard for how aquariums should be managed. A must visit for a walk along the sea wall while looking at the cedars stretching toward the sky. The little mermaid waits by the water.

A very beautiful and massive park. We rented bikes from the vicinity and rode around the whole park. Lots of opportunities to take some excellent pictures with beautiful views. Also took the hop on- hop off bus and it goes right through the park and you can see lots of beautiful views. will definitely go ride through this park again.

Love drives around the seawall, Stanley Park is an amazing gem within driving distance for anyone in the lower mainland. The sunsets across the inlet are amazing and the air is crisp and fresh. Make sure you visit this wonderful attraction if you get the chance!
Wonderful acoustics.  Great repertoire and celestial singing voices all the way from Cornell University,  Ithaca,  NY!
Got a tour. Missed the service. Beautiful church. Nice people.
Occasionally it holds West coast Symphonic orchestra concerts, that's why I go there

This is an open minded and forward thinking congregation. They are warm and friendly and welcoming to all.  Come as you are there's no judgement.  No matter your belief or scepticism...they are happy to meet you.

The stain glass windows alone will bring you joy!
Once the room erupts in song the acoustic pleasure is all yours to enjoy!

Great Dining Experience !! Splendid.. must try with your loved ones.. and first timers to the city of Vancouver.. !!
Amazing views from the top of the city.. and company of your nearest and dearest ones glass of fine wine.. and mouth watering appetizers.. what else you need for the perfect evening..??

So much more to Harbour Centre than the revolving restaurant. The food court is huge, lots of choice and places to sit. My two favourite shops are Morgan’s battery store, and Janet’s Sun Tailoring. Janet is the woman to see if you need any alternations made, she has done some amazing work for me and I higher recommend her. Security are on duty and regularly patrol the mall - the centre is clean and safe. Due to its downtown location, the BC liquor store (cold zone) is usually filled with interesting characters; it is small but has all of the essential food groups.

Great way to see all of Vancouver at one time. Amazing views. Quick going up. A bit scary going back down, but smooth ride. A bit too expensive but really enjoyed the experience. A must do when in Vancouver. I only went up the tower. I didnt check out any other parts of harbour center.

Food was good but a bit overpriced for what you get. 2 people on Valentine’s Day ended up being almost 300 bucks. Mandatory 18% tip too on Valentine’s Day. Has to book well in advance too. 

Service was fantastic and the views are great. Just pricey.

Wow we came to vancouver for a convention stop by had an incredible time. Fantastic home made food, authentic, fast service price is awesome and we felt at home. There was a live afrobeat drum band. lots of fun. Thanks for your hospitality. A must visit.

result.name: Dr. Sun Yat-Sen Classical Chinese Garden

reviews.text: The garden has a free side and a paid side. The free is nice place to go to get away from the city but it can get a bit muddy during after the rain and crowded during the weekend. The paid side is more serene and tranquil with covered areas and intimate gardens. There's even a small gallery with hot tea and a few other exhibits. I always enjoy going to the garden both on the paid and free sides.

Very zen place to visit. There is a little bit of something for everyone. There is a museum aspect to this classical Chinese garden and a tranquil park as well. There is normally koi fish swimming in the ponds but unfortunately they were not there on this trip. A must check out for tourists and anyone looking for a quite spot.

A little gem in the middle of a big city. As soon as you enter the garden, the city melts away. No noise pollution. The pond is nice to look at (even better in the later spring when the lily's are growing and the koi and turtles are out. It's just a nice break from the city.

This was one of our highlights on our trip. It's absolutely amazing and very much worth the admission fee. We could have spent the day there it's so beautiful. The tour guide was amazing. 
Be aware when you are walking there. Depending on how you get there, you essentially wak through "skid row" so I wouldn't recommend walking there at night or by yourself.

Having recently lived in China for 5 years, touring this garden brought back fond memories. While a little small, I could have easily seen myself relaxing there for an afternoon during the summertime. Still great to see on a cloudy day though.

Although a cathedral, the architecture and design here is much less flamboyant than many other cathedrals. But it is still replete with wonderful carved timbers. The building doesn't seem particularly big from the outside, but feels much more spacious on the inside. Very quiet during my visit.

What a beautiful worship service of celebration and inclusion. This is what heaven is like. Surrounded by multiple races and a wide spectrum of genders. As Jesus said, "Whosoever will may come!" Relevant application of Hosea to today's issues. Beautifully done. My heart is full, encouraged, and hope renewed!

If you are looking for some place for quiet reflection then you can come here and it is free entry and if you like can leave a donation before you leave.
 This is the oldest church in Vancouver and you can see it in the construction all around you. It is open during the week day especially on a Monday when we were here.
Beautiful church and the Good Noise Choir with Katherine Penfold as special guest was absolutely spectacular. Incredible performance by her and sounded so great with the choir.
Open for visitors with welcoming and helpful church attendants.

Came here for the planetarium, which was interesting. A mind-blowing and fascinating experience to be able to visualize how vast the universe really is. Planetarium was great, but other than that there just isn't really a lot to do here. The observatory was opened when we came, but because it was cloudy we couldn't look through any telescopes. Paid $15 for evening admission. Staff is friendly and knowledgeable.

This is small and mostly for kids but they staff was really great and helpful. They were very engaged and helpful and the whole day is filled with either a presentation or a movie. I saw presentations about science and fire as well as a really informative movie about dark matter. They also have a moon rock you can touch and a meteorite that you can lift.

I went here with my grade 3 class in 2016. The show was amazing and it felt like I was in space. We also made puppets and learned a lot about space. We saw how astronauts ate and drink in space and this is what lead me to become an astronaut (not yet, but future)

Small and expensive. Space exhibition is outdated and bland. The vancouver museum is better but too expensive. The best attraction is actually the building itself. There are some stunningly framed views of downtown vancouver. Best viewed in winter when the trees have lost their leafs. Entry should be free and would save them the cost of the 4 people sitting at the entry doing very little.

The planetarium is small, but you can see parts of a rocket, things of the space and specific expositions, like a Korean Vase exposition when I been here..
Also here have a cinema to watch about space or something like that.
I loved this place.

It's in a weird location between the gentrified Gastown and the low income Hastings. It does not feel very victory at all. The only purpose seems to be a landmark but I would not want to meet up with anyone there either. There is an underground toilet there which I hear is quite guarded so it is well maintained and clean. Although I have not had the courage to go down there yet.

I actually enjoy sitting out in this park. It feels like a nice sunny spot in the middle of the city.

Granted there are always some people of the streets in it, but that's part of the charm for me. You have students and people on lunch break and street folks all sitting around soaking up sun.

Not the place I'd make a special trip to hang out in, but if you're in need of a little space and breathing room in the middle of a day in Gastown this is a good pitstop to eat some takeout in the sun and people watch.

kind of an iconic spot in Vancouver, that is often pointed out in many movies and tv shows. Overall nice mixture of both younger and older people, and the area itself just has a very pleasant vibe overall. I recommend visiting if you have the chance to do so.

Well, my favorite building is across from Victory Square. There is always a mix of young and old here. Folks thriving beside folks barely surviving. Beautiful cenotaph that I will always visit and find beautiful.
Everyone there is happy. Just pot heads and  booze but no one wants anger there. Everyone is easy to talk to

Parking is ample. The planetarium, in reality, does cost money however it is really worth it. The brilliant trees, flora, and water functions were breathtaking. There has been a lovely little constructing to host a small wedding ceremony or event in. Outstanding vicinity to wander around. Very calm and tranquil. As a traveler, it won't be a completely attractive vicinity to go to however when you have greater days spending in Vancouver and are bored via common spots within the town, I would suggest to come back here and have some enjoyable time with a high-quality view.

The park becomes brilliant. The garden becomes very beautiful and it became calm surroundings. Parking becomes smooth to locate, but it is pay parking. First-rate views and top of the road dining. This area as a minimum is charming. I preserve coming lower back to it with my spouse and we love it. One of the fine places in Vancouver to head and revel in the best perspectives. Everything approximately this park is superb. The trees, the trees are stunning and thoroughly chopped and maintained.

Located at 4600 Cambie Street in Vancouver BC  near 33 Avenue and Cambie Street. One of the jewels of the Vancouver Parks Board.
This is a large treed park with a very nice restaurant located inside the park called Seasons in the Park. The food there is great and the staff there are very attentive.
If you are seated facing north there is a spectacular view of the skyline of downtown Vancouver and the north Shore Mountains.
The park is very well maintained and during the spring and summer months many wedding pictures and videos are shot there. 
A great place to visit regardless if you are a native or tourist.

Awesome park. They have lots of free parking and disabled parking too. They have a restaurant At the top of the park, a plant/bird conservatory (really cool), pitch and putt, basketball, tennis, rose garden and more. It’s one of my favourite parks. It’s super beautiful here almost all year long. It’s also a great place to walk your dog (on leash).

The park was wonderful. The Garden was very beautiful and it was a calm environment. Parking was easy to find, but it is pay parking. The fountain was great. It was nice to just sit back and watch the scenery around you. The view of the city is amazing from the park. You can see Grouse mountain as well as Mount Seymour. Downtown was visible to the left and Burnaby to the right. The park had many benches and public washrooms. Its a great place to go for a walk or a picnic on a sunny day.

I find the service is boring as hell but the building itself is beautiful. Definitely a place a couple would consider as an ideal church-wedding venue to tie the knot! People are kind and courteous too and very open to all walks of life.

Fairly friendly, but very old-fashioned and backwards. There was no sermon, only a man talking about his thoughts in regards to Jesus's parable on faith like a mustard seed. He outright said that Jesus was "wrong about that" more than once. The music was very old hymns, albeit played on an beautiful pipe organ. All in all, not a very good church in my opinion.
I tried phoning and emailing this church while visiting the Vancouver area right after Christmas. My husband and I were hoping to join in worship there. I’ve yet to get a response.

The most lovely of old Churches in the lower Mainland.  All the Ministers there deliver a message of spirituality, self love and peace within. If I lived in Vancouver, I would attend regularly. It's also a terrific venue for us musicians as our jazz is very much appreciated at their Sunday Vespers, as I am privileged to play with a number of groups who perform at this service.
Wow the VSO did a wonderful performance. Worth it for everyone. What a beautiful Church.
The teaching I heard was good.  People there are approachable and nice.  A negative, I'll keep to myself for now. ☺
Great venue. Fun event.
An extremely welcoming church with typically two services, one at 9am and another at 11am. Friendly greeters welcome you into the space. The music is moving and the speakers are thoughtful.
Nice place, we had our convocation there.

Reformed theology with Christ-centered gospel preaching. Complimentarian with a Mennonite Brethren statement of faith. A great godly community with alot of support in different ministry areas (kids ministry, justice and Mercy, weekly community group gatherings etc.). 

Come prepared to know Jesus Christ and to make Him known!

My most favourite spot in the city. Daffodils are starting to bloom now and it’s just so beautiful out. It’s a favourite spot for locals to stroll along and bike. The seawall is connected to Stanley Park.  Even on a crisp winter day, you’ll see people walking along with coffees in hand. Just up the block are myriad of eateries and ice cream shops. Grab a lunch to go and bring it down to the beach. 
There is also a wheelchair accessible walkway which they installed on the beach so you can get up close to the shoreline. 

The sunset is the most beautiful from this beach. And in the summer there are live performances and musicians. It’s just breathtaking.

Fun place for a day visit. Some pretty lights good for a nice stroll at night. In the summer, countless great memories at the Celebration of Lights! Get there by 8pm to easily find space for a bigger group (8+ people). Despite fighting through the crowd, 9pm works as well if you’re just a few people.

The beach was clean and the fresh breeze makes me feel comfortable and wants to go back again. It’s good for picnic and spending time with love ones. The beach was busy and well known for dating place.

There is no place else like this on earth. A true mix of everything urban and natural. Gateway to Stanley park which is the size of Manhattan. There are so many choices for dining or picnics on the beach. It gets crowded in the warm weather. Walk don't drive. Great for a quick bike or to just chill and read a book. Overcast rainy days are absolutely beautiful as well. Tennis. Volley ball, pitch and putt lawn bowling. It has lots to offer. And Stanley park brewing is a hop, skip and a jump too.

Nice views. Easy access. It's not My favorite beach in Vancouver,  but definitely a great place to get some sun, relax and read a book, or catch up with friends after work.
Summertime and sunsets :)
Beautiful Church I can spend hours walking inside.
Great experience in helping our local people in their over night/emerg. Cold sleeping. Hot meal anda bit of respect from everyone there. And I'm looking forward in help again out thus yr..
One of the best churches in Vancouver because they help the homeless and even give them a place to sleep once a week
Easy going Baptist church, welcoming all members of the community & visitors.
Friendly and Great staff

It was amazing to see my first love show here.
We sat up in the top area, third row and had a great show of the Wiggles.  At two years old my daughter had an amazing time. Sitting on my lap, we danced and sung along. Id recommend The Orpheum to anyone on Vancouver Island, such an experience.

Thank-you

The Orpheum is just a beautiful venue. The theatre is like something out of a movie, with the plush red carpet, brass bannisters, and ornate decorations, it’s just beautifully designed. There is also a lot of really cool history on display, including pictures of artists inducted into the B.C. Entertainment Hall of Fame. They also have plenty of concessions available though you meed to know to head upstairs as there is typically a longer lineup downstairs.

An iconic building in Vancouver, the  home of the Vancouver Symphony Orchestra. Came here after a long break to listen to Beethoven's 9th. The orchestra was the Vancouver Academy of Music and the singers were from the Vancouver Bach Choir.

The tickets were only $10 for open seating but we were given 2 tickets by our friends. So, it was even better.

We appreciated that young musician are learning and playing beautiful music.  It was a treat.

Soon there will be another program by the same orchestra. They will play the New World Symphony by Dvorak.
Theatre is a wonderful venue for comedy. We loved the snack and drink options available. Very roomy open lobby for hanging out prior to your show or event.

If you pay for meet and greet (most expensive tickets) have the meet and greet set up prior and preferably not up 10 flights of stairs.  Show was great but lack of planning for meet and great did not reflect well on the total experience.  Especially when we discovered on the way out there was an elevator. I am not a spring chicken and I have a bad drumstick!!

You could probably guess where they get the name from. A beautiful place to watch the sunset in the spring and summer times.

It's a fairly clean beach and even has a bathroom and concession stand. The sand can be a bit uncomfortable to sunbathe on, so I would recommend bringing multiple towels/blankets.

I love coming here with my kids. Its always Clean and free from Debris.  Sea shells are always on the beach and it is a great place to watch the Sunset. It is also great in the Summer for swimming in the Ocean.

The name says it all...
They do not get any more splendid..
and if you are a people watcher ....the path is great to walk or sit ..
bike ..run.... blade....✌️👽
I love how many people use this daily.. 365 rain or shine...
I'm sold...

It is a great place to walk, bike, play tennis, walk your dog, and play other activities. 
It is a crowded place during warmer months, but the view is amazing, the sunsets are spectacular. You can watch fireworks from this beach as well. Lots of places to eat along the beach.

I highly highly recommend this place.
It was amazing as you see on pictures.
I can't take my eyes off this beautiful sunset and nature.
I could see the most beautiful sunset in here and it would remain in my mind forever 😭🇨🇦
Cool local gallery and performance space.
Amazing space and environment for music. Fantastic events hosted here! Vintage, cozy and intimate.
Great place for art, dance, music or artistic expression in general
Jane Ellison's classes are a national treasure.
Showcases local talent

The best experience I have ever had in water sport. Kevin, their guide was awesome! We went to seadoo: ocean is yours tour. He explained a lot of stuff that I didn't knew. Went all the way to Bowen Island and Howe sound. Had a great swim in the middle of the ocean. I strongly recommend these guys if you're in Vancouver and interested in water sports. You'll see beautiful views from ocean which you can't see if you're on land or air. Kudos!
Did the Granite Falls zodiac tour with Yuri and had a great time.  Learned a lot about my own city and got to see the beautiful unspoiled nature that lies just minutes outside Vancouver.
Professional services and amazing experience. Interesting offer on every Monday, if you follow them on social media you pay just $10/h
Alex was our tour guide and we had a great tour. Alex was very kind and helpful. Showed us around a lot of beautiful sites. Will be back and will introduce our friends to come here

Had an amazing time with Clay and Paul, on this morning's (~3 hour) double seedo/jetski tour!

Was a great experience, guides were very friendly, saw some really cool things! Had a great opportunity to have fun! Would recommend!

It was much smaller than I expected, but admission is free/by donation. I enjoyed going through the exhibits. It's a quick cultural stop among shopping/eats nearby on Granville - It would probably take 20 min to go through everything.
Good spot for art work that doesn’t sacrifice meaning for the sake of creativity. Plus some lovely people who are willing to have a nice conversation.

Small and intimate gallery containing two rooms of contemporary art hosted by knowledgeable curators. The cag is the oldest gallery of its type in Vancouver and is worth a look, won't take much more than 30-50 minutes. They offer free lunchtime tours which are a great way to be introduced to the space. There's also a small bookshop and reference area. Free entry.
#cag #gallery #modernart
I'd love for the gallery to close a little bit later, but when it's full of expositions it's a really good place to spend some time.

Not for everyone. 
Contemporary art is always controversial. 
I was not impressed but you might love it. 

Venue is small but don’t need to have several galleries. 
Since there is no admission charge I didn’t feel I was cheated. 

Great clean space. 
Other than that it’s an art gallery.
